        "\n",
        "Each row is one eigenvector. Each column is one neuron. The number in each cell is the value of that eigenvector at that neuron : its strength at that position.\n",
        "The colour tells you the sign and magnitude:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Deep blue = strongly positive\n",
        "- Light blue = weakly positive\n",
        "- Light orange = weakly negative\n",
        "- Deep orange = strongly negative\n",
        "\n",
        "The orange-bordered columns are the two neurons that your input h stimulates. The dot product in the last column is computed by multiplying h's value (2.0) by the eigenvector's value at those two positions only because everywhere else h is zero and zero times anything is zero.\n",
        "\n",
        "When h stimulates neurons 1 and 2, it is like shining a spotlight on columns 1 and 2 of the grid. The dot product is asking: what colour are the cells under that spotlight in each row?\n",
        "If the spotlight lands on blue cells in the e1 row which is the positive dot product. If it lands on orange cells it is a negative dot product. If it lands on one blue and one orange of equal size: they cancel and the dot product is near zero."
